05469nam a22008055i 9781501749629DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019046308  a97815017496297 a10.1515/97815017496292doi  a(DE-B1597)541702  a(OCoLC)1124778673  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDA185b.L43 2020 4aDA185b.L43 2020 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a809/.93362231 aLears, Adin E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWorld of Echo :bNoise and Knowing in Late Medieval England /cAdin E. Lears. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b6 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: Voice in Medieval Soundscapes -- t1. "Clamor Iste Canor Est": Rolle's Heavenly Song and the Lay Theology of Noise -- t2. "Nota de Clamore": Echoic Mysticism and Margery Kempe's Clamorous Style -- t3. "Wondres to Here": Noise, Soundplay, and Langland's Poetics of Lolling in the Time of Wyclif -- t4. "Litel Sercles" of Sound: Resonance and the Noise of Language in Chaucer's House of Fame -- t5. "A Verray Jangleresse": Experience, Authority, and the Blisse of the Wife of Bath -- tEpilogue: Echoic Afterlives -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween late antiquity and the fifteenth century, theologians, philosophers, and poets struggled to articulate the correct relationship between sound and sense, creating taxonomies of sounds based on their capacity to carry meaning. In World of Echo, Adin E. Lears traces how medieval thinkers adopted the concept of noise as a mode of lay understanding grounded in the body and the senses.With a broadly interdisciplinary approach, Lears examines a range of literary genres to highlight the poetic and social effects of this vibrant discourse, offering close readings of works by Chaucer and Langland, as well as the mystics Richard Rolle and Margery Kempe. Each of these writers embraced an embodied experience of language resistant to clear articulation, even as their work reflects inherited anxieties about the appeal of such sensations. A preoccupation with the sound of language emerged in the form of poetic soundplay at the same time that mysticism and other forms of lay piety began to flower in England. As Lears shows, the presence of such emphatic aural texture amplified the cognitive importance of feeling in conjunction with reason and was a means for the laity-including lay women-to cultivate embodied forms of knowledge on their own terms, in precarious relation to existing clerical models of instruction. World of Echo offers a deep history of the cultural and social hierarchies that coalesce around the aesthetic experiences that accentuate ways of knowing outside proscribed models.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aNoisexSocial aspectszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aSoundxSocial aspectszEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEpistemology, Medieval thinking, sound and sense, Chaucer, Langland, Richard Rolle, and Margery Kempe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyt